. Young]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|on November 8, 1983, elected to fill vacancy\n|- \n|89th\n|[[Henry William Barnett]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|90th\n|[[Vincent Leibell]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|91st\n|[[William J. Ryan]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|- \n|92nd\n|[[Robert J. Connor]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|93rd\n|[[Eugene Levy (New York)|Eugene Levy]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|94th\n|[[Mary M. McPhillips]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|- \n|95th\n|[[William J. Larkin, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|- \n|96th\n|[[Lawrence E. Bennett]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|-\n|97th\n|[[Stephen M. Saland]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|98th\n|[[Richard I. Coombe]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|99th\n|[[Glenn E. Warren]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|100th\n|[[Neil W. Kelleher]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|101st\n|[[Maurice D. Hinchey]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|- \n|102nd\n|[[Clarence D. Lane]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|103rd\n|[[Michael J. Hoblock, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|104th\n|[[Richard J. Conners]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|- \n|rowspan=\"2\" | 105th\n|([[Gail S. Shaffer]])*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|on January 1, 1983, appointed as [[Secretary of State of New York]]\n|-\n|[[Paul D. Tonko]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|on April 12, 1983, elected to fill vacancy<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/04/13/nyregion/stavisky-wins-race-for-state-senate.html ''STAVISKY WINS RACE FOR STATE SENATE; ...Paul Tonko, of Amsterdam, a Democrat, was the winner...''] in ''The New York Times'' on April 13, 1983</ref>\n|- \n|106th\n|[[Michael R. McNulty]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|107th\n|[[James Tedisco]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|108th\n|[[Robert A. D'Andrea]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|109th\n|[[Glenn H. Harris]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|110th\n|[[Andrew W. Ryan, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|111th\n|[[John W. McCann]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|- \n|112th\n|[[John G. A. O'Neil]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|113th\n|[[Anthony J. Casale]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|114th\n|[[H. Robert Nortz]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|115th\n|[[William R. Sears (New York)|William R. Sears]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|- \n|116th\n|[[Richard S. Ruggiero]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|-\n|117th\n|[[Ray T. Chesbro]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|118th\n|[[Michael J. Bragman]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|119th\n|[[William E. Bush]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|120th\n|[[Melvin N. Zimmer]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|121st\n|[[Hyman M. Miller]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|122nd\n|[[Clarence D. Rappleyea, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|Minority Leader<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/02/06/nyregion/gop-minority-elevates-4.html ''G.O.P. MINORITY ELEVATES 4''] by Frank Lynn, in ''The New York Times'' on February 6, 1983</ref>\n|-\n|123rd\n|[[James W. McCabe]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|-\n|124th\n|[[James R. Tallon, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|- \n|125th\n|[[Hugh S. MacNeil]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|- \n|126th\n|[[George H. Winner, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|127th\n|[[Randy Kuhl]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|128th\n|[[Michael F. Nozzolio]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|129th\n|[[Frank G. Talomie Sr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|130th\n|[[Louise M. Slaughter]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|-\n|131st\n|[[Gary Proud]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./RTL\n|\n|- \n|132nd\n|[[Pinny Cooke]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|133rd\n|[[David F. Gantt]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|134th\n|[[Roger J. Robach]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons./RTL\n|\n|- \n|135th\n|[[James F. Nagle]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|136th\n|[[Richard C. Wesley]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|137th\n|[[R. Stephen Hawley]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|138th\n|[[Joseph T. Pillittere]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./RTL\n|\n|- \n|139th\n|[[Matthew J. Murphy, Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|140th\n|[[Robin L. Schimminger]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|\n|-\n|141st\n|[[Arthur O. Eve]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|- \n|142nd\n|[[John B. Sheffer II]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Republican\n|\n|-\n|143rd\n|[[Dennis T. Gorski]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|144th\n|[[William B. Hoyt]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|- \n|145th\n|[[Richard J. Keane]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|146th\n|[[Francis J. Pordum]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./RTL\n|\n|-\n|147th\n|[[L. William Paxon]]\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|148th\n|[[Vincent J. Graber Sr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Cons.\n|\n|- \n|149th\n|[[Daniel B. Walsh]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|Majority Leader\n|-\n|150th\n|[[William L. Parment]]\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|}\n\n===Employees===\n* Clerk: [[Catherine A. Carey]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/04/nyregion/voting-in-new-york-state-for-61-seats-in-the-senate.html ''VOTING IN NEW YORK STATE FOR 61 SEATS IN THE SENATE''] in ''[[The New York Times]]'' on November 4, 1982\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/1982/11/04/nyregion/vote-totals-for-races-in-the-new-york-state-assembly.html ''VOTE TOTALS FOR RACES IN THE NEW YORK STATE ASSEMBLY''] in ''The New York Times'' on November 4, 1982\n\n{{NYLegislatures}}\n\n[[Category:New York (state) legislative sessions|185]]\n[[Category:1983 in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:1984 in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|NewYork state legislative session}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox New York Legislature\n|number = 185th\n|image = \n|imagename = \n|imagedate = \n|start = January 1, 1983\n|end = December 31, 1984\n|vp = Lt. Gov. [[Alfred DelBello]] (D)\n|pro tem = [[Warren M. Anderson]] (R)\n|speaker = [[Stanley Fink]] (D)\n|senators = 61\n|reps = 150\n|s-majority = Republican (35\u201326)\n|h-majority = Democratic (98\u201352)\n|sessionnumber1 = 1st\n|sessionstart1 = January 5\n|sessionend1 = June 28, 1983\n|sessionnumber2 = 2nd\n|sessionstart2 = September 15, 1983\n|sessionnumber3 = 3rd\n|sessionstart3 = January 4\n|sessionend3 = July 1, 1984\n|sessionnumber4 = 4th\n|sessionstart4 = December 6, 1984\n|previous = 184th\n|next = 186th\n}}\n\nThe '''185th New York State Legislature''', consisting of the [[New York State Senate]] and the [[New York State Assembly]], met from January 5, 1983, to December 31, 1984, during the first and second years of [[Mario Cuomo]]'s [[Governor of New York|governorship]], in [[Albany, New York|Albany]].\n\n==Background==\nOn May 8, 1982, Senate Republicans and Assembly Democrats announced that they had agreed upon a new apportionment. The number of seats in the State Senate was increased from 60 to 61.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/09/nyregion/districting-plan-drawn-in-albany-some-incumbents-may-lose-seats.html ''DISTRICTING PLAN DRAWN IN ALBANY; SOME INCUMBENTS MAY LOSE SEATS''] by E. J. Dionne Jr, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on May 9, 1982</ref> The new district lines were [[gerrymander]]ed by the Republican Senate majority to increase Republican strength, and by the Democratic Assembly majority to increase Democratic strength.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/05/16/nyregion/how-new-lines-will-affect-political-races.html ''HOW NEW LINES WILL AFFECT POLITICAL RACES''] by James Feron, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on May 16, 1982</ref>\n\nOn June 23, 1982, a special panel of three federal judges ordered Special Master Robert P. Patterson Jr. to revise the new apportionment proposed by the Legislature.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/06/24/nyregion/court-appointees-to-modify-redistricting-plan-for-state.html ''COURT APPOINTEES TO MODIFY REDISTRICTING PLAN FOR STATE''] by Arnold H. Lubasch, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on June 24, 1982</ref>\n\nOn July 3, 1982, the revised re-apportionment was approved by the [[U.S. Department of Justice]].<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1982/07/04/nyregion/new-redistricting-by-new-york-state-is-approved-by-us.html ''NEW REDISTRICTING BY NEW YORK STATE IS APPROVED BY U.S.''] by Jane Perlez, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on July 4, 1982</ref>\n\nThus, under the provisions of the [[New York Constitution]] of 1938 and the U.S. Supreme Court decision to follow the [[One man, one vote]] rule, re-apportioned in 1982 by the Legislature, 61 Senators and 150 assemblymen were elected in single-seat districts for two-year terms. Senate and Assembly districts consisted of approximately the same number of inhabitants, the area being apportioned contiguously without restrictions regarding county boundaries.\n\nAt this time there were two major political parties: the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]] and the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]]. The [[Conservative Party of New York State|Conservative Party]], the [[Liberal Party of New York|Liberal Party]], the [[New York State Right to Life Party|Right to Life Party]], the [[Libertarian Party (United States)|Libertarian Party]], a \"Statewide Independent Party\", a \"Unity Party\", the [[New Alliance Party]], and the [[Socialist Workers Party (United States)|Socialist Workers Party]] also nominated tickets.\n\n==Elections==\nThe [[New York gubernatorial election, 1982|New York state election, 1982]], was held on November 2. Lieutenant Governor [[Mario Cuomo]] was elected Governor, and Westchester County Executive [[Alfred DelBello]] was elected Lieutenant Governor, both Democrats. The elections to the other three statewide elective offices resulted in the re-election of the three incumbent officeholders: a Republican Comptroller, a Democratic Attorney General and a Democratic U.S. Senator. The approximate party strength at this election, as expressed by the vote for Governor, was: Democrats 2,560,000; Republicans 2,249,000; Conservatives 230,000; Liberals 116,000; Right to Life 52,000; Libertarians 17,000; Statewide Independents 16,000; Unity 6,000; New Alliance 5,000; and Socialist Workers 4,000.\n\nSixteen of the nineteen women members of the previous legislature\u2014State Senators [[Carol Berman]] (Dem.), of [[Lawrence, Nassau County, New York|Lawrence]]; [[Mary B. Goodhue]] (Rep.), a lawyer of [[Mount Kisco, New York|Mount Kisco]]; [[Olga A. M\u00e9ndez]] (Dem.), of [[East Harlem]], and [[Linda Winikow]] (Dem.), of [[Spring Valley, New York|Spring Valley]]; and Assemblywomen [[Elizabeth Connelly]] (Dem.), of [[Staten Island]]; [[Pinny Cooke]] (Rep.), of [[Rochester, New York|Rochester]]; [[Geraldine L. Daniels]] (Dem.), of [[the Bronx]]; [[Gloria Davis (politician)|Gloria Davis]] (Dem.), of [[the Bronx]]; [[Eileen C. Dugan]] (Dem.), of [[Brooklyn]]; [[Aurelia Greene]] (Dem.), of [[the Bronx]]; [[Rhoda S. Jacobs]] (Dem.), of [[Brooklyn]]; [[Gerdi E. Lipschutz]] (Dem.), of [[Queens]]; [[May W. Newburger]] (Dem.), of [[Great Neck, New York|Great Neck]]; [[Toni Rettaliata]] (Rep.), of [[Huntington, New York|Huntington]]; [[Gail S. Shaffer]] (Dem.), of [[North Blenheim, New York|North Blenheim]]; and [[Helene Weinstein]] (Dem.), a lawyer of [[Brooklyn]]\u2014were re-elected. [[Anna V. Jefferson]] (Dem.), an accountant of [[Brooklyn]], was also elected to the State Senate. [[Cynthia Jenkins]] (Dem.), a librarian of [[Queens]]; [[Helen M. Marshall]] (Dem.), a teacher and librarian of [[Queens]]; [[Nettie Mayersohn]] (Dem.), of [[Queens]]; [[Mary M. McPhillips]] (Dem.), of [[Middletown, Orange County, New York|Middletown]]; [[Barbara Patton]] (Dem.), a lawyer of [[Hempstead, New York|Hempstead]]; and [[Louise M. Slaughter]] (Dem.), of [[Fairport, New York|Fairport]]; were also elected to the Assembly. Gail S. Shaffer did not take her seat in the Assembly, and was appointed as [[Secretary of State of New York]] instead.\n\nOn May 24, 1983, [[Julia Harrison]] (Dem.), of [[Queens]], was elected to fill a vacancy in the Assembly. Thus the 185th Legislature finished having 23 women members, surpassing the previous record of 19 in the [[184th New York State Legislature]] (in 1982).\n\nThe New York state election, 1983, was held on November 8. One vacancy in the Assembly was filled.\n\n==Sessions==\nThe Legislature met for the first regular session (the 206th) at the State Capitol in [[Albany, New York|Albany]] on January 5, 1983;<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/01/06/nyregion/cuomo-issues-call-for-partnership-to-spark-growth.html ''CUOMO ISSUES CALL FOR \"PARTNERSHIP\" TO SPARK GROWTH''] by Josh Barbanel, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on January 6, 1983</ref> and recessed indefinitely on June 28.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/06/29/nyregion/cuomo-expects-new-bond-issue-to-rebuild-state.html ''CUOMO EXPECTS NEW BOND ISSUE TO REBUILD STATE''] by Josh Barbanel, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on June 29, 1983</ref>\n\n[[Stanley Fink]] (Dem.) was re-elected [[Speaker of the New York State Assembly|Speaker of the Assembly]].\n\n[[Warren M. Anderson]] (Rep.) was re-elected [[Temporary President of the New York State Senate|Temporary President of the Senate]].\n\nThe Legislature met for a special session on September 15, 1983, to consider changes to the laws concerning transportation of cargoes.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1983/09/16/nyregion/bill-approved-to-permit-bigger-trucks-on-roads.html ''BILL APPROVED TO PERMIT BIGGER TRUCKS ON ROADS''] by Edward A. Gargan, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on September 16, 1983</ref>\n\nThe Legislature met for the second regular session (the 207th) at the State Capitol in Albany on January 4, 1984;<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/01/05/nyregion/cuomo-proposes-a-broad-agenda-in-annual-speech.html ''CUOMO PROPOSES A BROAD AGENDA IN ANNUAL SPEECH''] by Josh Barbanel, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on January 5, 1984</ref> and recessed indefinitely shortly before 2 a.m. on July 1.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/07/02/nyregion/after-one-final-battle-legislature-goes-home.html ''AFTER ONE FINAL BATTLE, LEGISLATURE GOES HOME''] by Edward A. Gargan, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on July 2, 1984</ref>\n\nAn hour after midnight, on May 30, the State Assembly rejected after a stormy debate of many hours the proposal to raise the [[legal drinking age]] from 19 to 21 years; the vote stood 80 to 69.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/05/30/nyregion/measure-to-raise-drinking-age-to-21-loses-in-new-york.html ''MEASURE TO RAISE DRINKING AGE TO 21 LOSES IN NEW YORK''] by Michael Oreskes, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on May 30, 1984</ref>\n\nThe Legislature met for another special session on December 6, 1984. At this session, the legislators raised the wages of the legislators who were elected to the next Legislature; approved a sales tax increase for Erie County; and extended a corporate tax surcharge used to subsidize the New York City mass transit system.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/1984/12/07/nyregion/extension-of-tax-to-retain-fares-voted-in-albany.html ''EXTENSION OF TAX TO RETAIN FARES VOTED IN ALBANY''] by Michael Oreskes, in the ''[[New York Times]]'' on December 7, 1984</ref>\n\n==State Senate==\n\n===Senators===\nThe asterisk (*) denotes members of the previous Legislature who continued in office as members of this Legislature. Andrew Jenkins and Lloyd Stephen Riford Jr. changed from the Assembly to the Senate at the beginning of this Legislature. Assemblyman Leonard P. Stavisky was elected to fill a vacancy in the Senate.\n\n'''Note:''' For brevity, the chairmanships omit the words \"...the Committee on (the)...\"\n\n{| class=wikitable\n! District\n! Senator\n! Party\n! Notes\n|-\n|1st\n|[[Kenneth LaValle]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|2nd\n|[[James J. Lack]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|3rd\n|[[Caesar Trunzo]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|4th\n|[[Owen H. Johnson]]*        \n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|5th\n|[[Ralph J. Marino]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|6th\n|[[John R. Dunne]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|7th\n|[[Michael J. Tully Jr.]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|\n|-\n|8th\n|[[Norman J. Levy]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons.\n|Chairman of Transportation\n|-\n|9th\n|[[Carol Berman]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|10th\n|[[Andrew Jenkins (politician)|Andrew Jenkins]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|\n|-\n|11th\n|[[Frank Padavan]]*\n|{{Party shading/Republican}} | Rep./Cons./RTL\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=\"2\" | 12th\n|[[Gary L. Ackerman]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Dem./Lib.\n|on March 1, 1983, elected to the [[98th United States Congress|98th U.S. Congress]]\n|-\n|[[Leonard P. Stavisky]]*\n|{{Party shading/Democratic}} | Democrat\n|on April 12, 1983, elected to fill vacancy<ref>[https: