jian leaders}}\n}}\n{{Navboxes\n|title = International\n|list1 =\n{{Currentcommunistrulers}}\n{{List of Current Heads of State of G20}}\n{{Current G20 Leaders}}\n{{BRICS}}\n{{Current APEC Leaders}}\n{{Current SCO Leaders}}\n}}\n|titlestyle=background: #CC0000; color:gold;}}\n{{Portal bar|China|Biography|Politics}}\n{{Subject bar|commons=y|n=y|n-search=Category:Xi Jinping|wikt=y|wikt-search=Category:en:Xi Jinping|q=y|s=y|s-search=Author:Xi Jinping|d=y|d-search=Q15031}}{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Xi, Jinping}}\n[[Category:Xi Jinping| ]]\n[[Category:Xi Jinping family| ]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Chinese politicians]]\n[[Category:21st-century Chinese politicians]]\n[[Category:Chinese nationalists]]\n[[Category:Philosophers from Beijing]]\n[[Category:Communist rulers]]\n[[Category:Communist Party of China politicians from Beijing]]\n[[Category:General Secretaries and Chairmen of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:Governors of Fujian]]\n[[Category:Governors of Zhejiang]]\n[[Category:Members of the 17th Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:Members of the 18th Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:Members of the 19th Politburo Standing Committee of the Communist Party of China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China politicians from Beijing]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Nishan-e-Pakistan]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Olympic Order]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Abdulaziz al Saud]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of Jos\u00e9 Marti]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of St. Andrew]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Liberator]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Order of the Republic (Serbia)]]\n[[Category:Chinese male writers]]\n[[Category:Sent-down youths]]\n[[Category:Tsinghua University alumni]]\n[[Category:Vice Presidents of the People's Republic of China]]\n[[Category:People's Republic of China philosophers]]\n[[Category:Victims of the Cultural Revolution]]\n[[Category:Chinese expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:Communist writers]]\n[[Category:Chinese Marxists]]\n", "name_user": "BirdValiant", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid change \"some political observers\" back to \"many political observers\". Please do not mark these changes as \"minor\".)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Xi_Jinping"}
{"title_page": "McGill School of Architecture", "text_new": "{{Infobox university\n|name        = McGill School of Architecture\n|other_names = Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture\n|image       = McGill_School_of_Architecture_logo.jpg\n|image_size  = 250px\n|caption     = Macdonald-Harrington Building\n|image_alt   = An artistic representation of the Macdonald-Harrington Building which is often used as a logo for the School of Architecture.\n|established = {{start date and age|1896}}\n|type        = [[Architecture school]]\n|founder     = [[William Christopher Macdonald]]\n|parent      = [[McGill University]]<br>[[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]]\n|staff       = 7<ref name=Staff>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/faculty/staff|title=Staff|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n|faculty     = 44<ref name=Faculty>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/faculty|title=Faculty and Staff|publisher= Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427200649/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/faculty|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|director    = Martin Bressani\n|students    = 273 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/es/registration-statistics|title=Enrollment Reports|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190924133447/https://www.mcgill.ca/es/registration-statistics|archive-date=24 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|undergrad   = 163 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment />\n|postgrad    = 90 (Fall 2019)<ref name=Enrollment />\n|doctoral    = 20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/phd-students|title=Current Ph.D. students|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427200532/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/phd-students|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|address     = [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]]\n|city        = [[Montreal]]\n|province    = [[Quebec]]\n|country     = Canada\n|postcode    = H3A 2K6\n|language    = English and French\n|free_label  = Accreditation\n|free        = {{hlist|[[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|CACB]]|[[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards|NCARB]]}}\n|coordinates = {{coord |45.5053|-73.5758|type:edu_region:CA-QC|display=inline,title}}\n|campus      = [[urban area|Urban]] \n|website     = {{url|https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/}}\n}}\n\nThe '''McGill School of Architecture''' (officially the '''Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture''' since 2017) is one of eight [[academic department|academic units]] constituting the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]] at [[McGill University]] in [[Montreal]], [[Quebec]], Canada. Founded in 1896 by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]], it is among the oldest [[architecture schools]] in [[North America]],<ref name=History>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history|title=History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133125/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> offering accredited professional and post-professional programs ranging from undergraduate to PhD levels.<ref name=Programs>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs|title=Programs|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427200818/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/programs|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Since its founding, the School has established an international reputation and a record of producing leading professionals and researchers who have helped shape the field of architecture, including [[Moshe Safdie]], [[Arthur Erickson]], [[Raymond Moriyama]] and the founders of [[Arcop]].{{NoteTag|The founders of Arcop include [[Ray Affleck]], Guy Desbarats, Jean Michaud, [[:fr:Fred Lebensold|Fred Lebensold]], [[Hazen Sise]] and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]], all graduates and/or professors at the School of Architecture at some point.<ref name=Arcop>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379565/affleck-desbarats-dimakopoulos-lebensold-sise-fonds|title=Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise fonds|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327180019/https://www.cca.qc.ca/en/archives/379565/affleck-desbarats-dimakopoulos-lebensold-sise-fonds|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}}<ref name=Alumni>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427201100/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nHaving existed during both [[World war|World Wars]] and the development of [[Modern architecture|Modernism]], the School experienced many changes in terms of enrollment and architectural ideologies over the course of its history. Beginning with a class of only three students, the School expanded many times and relocated on multiple occasions to different buildings both on and off of McGill's main campus. It was the first architecture school in Canada to offer a graduate [[urban planning|planning]] program and a PhD in Architecture,<ref name=CanadianArchitect /> and the first department within the Faculty of Engineering to graduate women.<ref name=McGillEngineering>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/about-us/our-history/1900-1950|title=1900-1950 - McGill Faculty of Engineering History|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=5 April 2020}}</ref> Several of its directors and staff founded architecture schools at other universities.{{NoteTag|Universities where Schools of Architecture were founded by McGill faculty include [[Victoria University of Manchester]] (1903),<ref name=McGillBeginning /> [[University of British Columbia]] (1950),<ref name=SALA /> [[Technical University of Nova Scotia]] (1961) and [[Carleton University]] (1968).<ref name=Shadbolt />}} \n\nThe School of Architecture is located inside the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], designed by [[Andrew Taylor (architect)|Sir Andrew Taylor]], on the McGill University downtown campus.<ref name=CAC>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/campus/buildings/Macdonald-Harrington.html|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building (formerly Macdonald Chemistry Building)|publisher=Canadian Architecture Collection, McGill Archives|accessdate=18 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190903145907/http://cac.mcgill.ca/campus/buildings/Macdonald-Harrington.html|archive-date=3 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]], which became independent from the School of Architecture in 1970, occupies the fourth floor.<ref name=UrbanPlanning /> The School of Architecture also operates many auxiliary facilities, including workshops, laser cutting and 3D-printing facilities, research labs and various libraries and collections both within the Macdonald-Harrington Building and elsewhere on McGill's campus. The School is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB) and is recognized in the United States by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB).<ref name=Accreditation>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/accreditation|title=Accreditation|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323052933/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/accreditation|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nThe [[#Architecture Students' Association (ASA)|Architecture Students' Association]] represents undergraduate students at the School<ref name=ASA /> and the [[#Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA)|Graduate Architecture Students' Association]] represents graduate and post-graduate students.<ref name=GASA /> All registered students automatically become members of these associations. The School also maintains a chapter of the [[American Institute of Architecture Students]]<ref name=AIAS /> as well as bilateral exchange agreements with several architecture schools in other countries.<ref name=Exchange /> Admission to the School is highly competitive and enrollment represents one of the highest percentages of female students at McGill.<ref name=Stats /><ref name=CACB /> As of Fall 2019, there were 163 undergraduate, 90 graduate and 20 PhD students enrolled.<ref name=Enrollment />\n\nOn September 26, 2017, the School was renamed the Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture following a [[Canadian dollar|C]]$12&nbsp;million gift from architect and McGill graduate Peter Fu.<ref name=Fu>{{cite web | url=https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/chinese-architect-peter-guo-hua-fu-donated-12-million-to-the-mcgill-school-of-architecture_o | title=Chinese Architect Peter Guo-hua Fu Donated $12 Million to the McGill School of Architecture | publisher=Architect Magazine | author=Ayda Ayoubi | year=2017 | accessdate=2 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220518/https://www.architectmagazine.com/design/chinese-architect-peter-guo-hua-fu-donated-12-million-to-the-mcgill-school-of-architecture_o | archive-date=12 January 2020 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nMcGill's School of Architecture, founded in 1896, is one of the oldest architecture schools in North America and the second to be established in Canada.<!-- University of Toronto had the first architecture program in Canada (1890)--><ref name=History /> Initially a [[Beaux-Arts architecture|Beaux-Arts]] style school based in the [[Arts and Crafts movement]], it became a [[Bauhaus]]-based institution under new directorship after [[World War&nbsp;II]]. The School was the first in the country to offer a graduate planning program and a PhD in Architecture.<ref name=CanadianArchitect>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/glaciermedia/docs/canadian_architect_october_2014|title=State of the Schools - Canadian Architect October Issue 2014|page=18|publisher=Canadian Architect|date=October 2014|author=Annmarie Adams|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Early history===\n[[File:William Christopher Macdonald.jpg|thumb|upright|[[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]], 4th [[List of McGill University people#List of chancellors|Chancellor of McGill University]], created a Chair in Architecture at McGill in 1896.]]\nIn 1890, the [[Ordre des architectes du Qu\u00e9bec|Province of Quebec Association of Architects]] adopted a constitution requiring compulsory examination for people in Quebec who wished to become professional architects. This created a need for more systematic architectural education, and the absence of such opportunities caused many aspiring Canadian architects to study in the United States, where ten architecture schools had already been established.<ref name=History /> Canada did not yet have any formal architectural education, and the only forms of architectural education in Montreal were periodical lectures by local practising architects at McGill's affiliated religious colleges. This new need for architectural education is an important factor that led to the founding of the School of Architecture at McGill University.<ref name=McGillBeginning>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/beginning|title=The beginning with Stewart H. Capper, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133044/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/beginning|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1896, [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William C. Macdonald]] created a chair in architecture at McGill which was led by [[Stewart Henbest Capper]], a former student at the [[\u00c9cole des Beaux-Arts]] in Paris. Macdonald also provided funds for the purchase and maintenance of the School's initial equipment. At this time, the School had two architecture studios which occupied two rooms of the top floor of the original Macdonald Engineering Building. The School offered a four-year course to prepare students for professional accreditation, and as it remains today, the first year was preparatory, with all courses taken jointly by architecture and engineering students. The first graduating class was composed of only three students,{{NoteTag|The first graduating class was composed of Frank Peder, George Taylor Hyde and Norman M. McLeod.<ref name=McGillBeginning />}} and Professor Capper gave all lectures in architecture, while Henry F. Armstrong, the only other full-time professor, taught art classes and modelling.<ref name=McGillBeginning />\n\n[[File:McDonald Engineering Building, McGill University, Montreal, QC, about 1895.jpg|thumb|left|upright|200px|The old [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#Buildings & Laboratories|Macdonald Engineering Building]], the School of Architecture's original home.]]\nIn 1903, Capper returned to England to establish the School of Architecture at [[Victoria University of Manchester]], which was the fourth university architecture school to be established in the British Commonwealth, after [[University of Toronto]] (1890), [[University of Liverpool]] (1894) and McGill (1896).<ref name=McGillBeginning /> The second director of the School, [[Percy Nobbs]], arrived at McGill in 1903 to only two students. Nobbs is credited with designing the [[McGill University#University identity and culture|McGill coat of arms]] three years into his tenure.<ref name=McGillEngineering /> As director, he divided the four-year course into two streams, the BArch degree and the BSc degree in Architectural Engineering. By 1906, he was teaching six classes, so he hired three new staff to assist him, including his former colleague [[Cecil Burgess]]. Nobbs believed students should be exposed to architecture in practice, and designed the McGill Union (today the [[McCord Museum]]) across from McGill's [[Roddick Gates]]. After the Macdonald Engineering Building burned down in 1907,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/campus/buildings/Macdonald_Engineering.html|title=Macdonald Engineering, the Workman Wing, & the Electrical Wing|publisher=Canadian Architecture Collection|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref> Nobbs designed the new building in its place, and the School of Architecture moved to its ground floor. By 1912, the School had grown to eight students, and the next year, [[Philip J. Turner]] joined the faculty.<ref name=McGillNobbs>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/nobbs|title=Legacy of Nobbs, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133138/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/nobbs|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1913, [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] became the new director. He is credited with designing the McGill flag, which he presented to the university in 1921 and has since flown above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]].<ref name=McGillTraquair>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/traquair|title=Legacy of Traquair, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133621/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/traquair|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/details/McGillLibrary-cac_finding-aid_ramsay-traquair-book1-guide-18112/page/n21/mode/2up|title=Ramsay Traquair and his successors : guide to the Archive|date=1987|page=134|publisher=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art, McGill University|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref> \n[[File:Arts Building, McGill University.jpg|thumb|upright|The McGill flag, designed by [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] and presented to McGill in 1921, flown above the [[McCall MacBain Arts Building|Arts Building]].]] \n\n====World War I====\nAt the onset of World War I, many faculty and students were called to war. Nobbs attained the military rank of [[Major (United Kingdom)|major]], while twelve of his students did not return. Four among these students have tributes named in their honour at McGill, including Gordon H. Blackader, for whom the [[McGill School of Architecture#Libaries and collections|Blackader-Lauterman Library]] is named, Hugh McLennan, namesake of the ''Hugh McLennan Memorial Travelling Scholarship'', Murdoch Laing, of the ''Murdoch Laing Prize'' and John Louis Robertson, of the ''Louis Robertson Book Prize''. In addition to the aforementioned four, eight other McGill architects were added to the [[World War I casualties|Roll of Honour]] of World War I.{{NoteTag|McGill architects who fell during World War I include Gunner A.I. Richardson (Arch. '11), Robert W.S. Robertson (Arch. '16), Private Allen D. Harvey (Arch. '17), Private Archibald McLeod (Arch. '15), Lieutenant George D. McLeod (Arch. '15), Lieutenant Clarke H. Popham (Arch. '17) and Captain Benjamin B. McConkey (Arch. '14).<ref name=McGillTraquair />}} Another seven graduates returned from the war as distinguished soldiers, with one receiving the [[Distinguished Service Order]], four the [[Military Cross]] and two the French ''[[Croix de Guerre]]''.{{NoteTag|McGill graduates who distinguished themselves in service to Canada during World War I were Major Walter C. Hyde (Arch. '15), who received the [[Distinguished Service Order]], Lieutenants S.M. Sproule (Arch. '12), W.A.I. Anglin (Arch. '16), K.G. Blackader (Arch.'19) and G.A. Birks (Arch. '19), who received the [[Military Cross]] and Lieutenants P.E. Amos (Arch. '19) and H.P. Illsley (Arch. '17), recipients of the ''[[Croix de Guerre]]'' of France.<ref name=McGillTraquair />}}<ref name=McGillTraquair />\n\n====Post-war====\nAfter the war, Nobbs continued to teach many classes. In 1920, [[Ernest Cormier]] joined the faculty for one year to teach design<ref name=McGillTraquair /><ref name=Cormier>{{cite web|url=https://www.pc.gc.ca/en/culture/clmhc-hsmbc/res/doc/information-backgrounder/Ernest_Cormier|title=Ernest Cormier (1885-1980)|publisher=Parks Canada|accessdate=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191208215909/https://www.pc.gc.ca/en/culture/clmhc-hsmbc/res/doc/information-backgrounder/Ernest_Cormier|archive-date=8 December 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and the next year, Traquair organized the School's first \"sketching school\" in [[Quebec City]],<ref name=McGillTraquair /> a tradition that has been carried on annually to various destinations since as a credited course.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/sketchingschool|title=Summer Sketching School|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323053117/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/sketchingschool|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Arthur Lismer]], a member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught this course at the School for over a decade even after his retirement in 1955.<ref name=McGillForties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/forties|title=The School with John Bland:1940s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133355/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/forties|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Lismer>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/library/channels/event/exhibition-arthur-lismers-mcgill-sketchbook-240235|title=Exhibition: Arthur Lismer\u2019s McGill Sketchbook|publisher=McGill Library|year=2015|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150221050552/http://www.mcgill.ca/library/channels/event/exhibition-arthur-lismers-mcgill-sketchbook-240235|archive-date=21 February 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 1939, Turner succeeded Traquair, who had completed a 26-year tenure as director. At this time, McGill Principal [[Lewis Williams Douglas]] considered discontinuing the architecture program due to low enrollment; however he faced a great deal of backlash from Turner and several famous architects from Montreal, and eventually abandoned the idea.<ref name=Turner>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/turner|title=Legacy of Turner, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133816/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/turner|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Under Turner's tenure, support for co-education was made,<ref name=Turner /> and in 1943 [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]] became the School's first female graduate.<ref>{{cite web|title=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative|url=http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=5164|website=Canadian Women Artists History Initiative|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150910171223/http://cwahi.concordia.ca/sources/artists/displayArtist.php?ID_artist=5164|archive-date=10 September 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Wisnicki became the fourth female member of the [[Ontario Association of Architects]] and the second to join the [[Architectural Institute of British Columbia]].<ref name=Wisnicki>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/catherine-mary-wisnicki|title=Catherine Wisnicki|author=Annmarie Adams|date=22 September 2017|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190608233224/https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/catherine-mary-wisnicki|archive-date=8 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Mid-century===\nFollowing the retirement of Turner as director of the School of Architecture, [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] became director in 1941. In 1945, a new five-year program was adopted for the next two decades. After the [[World War Two|Second World War]], the School of Architecture increased its staff and doubled its physical accommodation due to the surge in university enrollment. This required the School to briefly use McGill's [[Dawson College]], a [[satellite campus]] in St. Jean, Quebec, to accommodate its students. By 1947, the School had become so cramped that a repurposed building on University Street was vacated to make room for the School's students. This new building expanded the School's physical size immensely, and enrollment grew to 133 full-time students by the 1949\u20131950 academic year.<ref name=McGillForties /> At the same time as the School's relocation, Professor Frederic Lasserre left the School to establish a new architecture school the [[University of British Columbia]].{{NoteTag|McGill Architecture graduates [[Catherine Mary Wisnicki]]<!--listed in source by maiden name Catherine Chard-->, [[Peter Oberlander]] and [[Arthur Erickson]] became teachers at Lasserre's new school in its formative years.<ref name=McGillForties />}}<ref name=SALA>{{cite web|url=https://sala.ubc.ca/about/history|title=History|publisher=University of British Columbia School of Architecture + Landscape Architecture|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200326033712/https://sala.ubc.ca/about/history|archive-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Lasserre's resignation, coupled with the new influx of students at the School resulted in the hiring of several new faculty members, which included [[Robert Esdaile]] and [[Harold Spence-Sales]].<ref name=McGillForties /> \n\nIn 1946, Spence-Sales became Associate Professor of Design, and he and Bland established the first post-graduate architecture and planning program in Canada. Beginning in this academic year, the professional program was extended to six years, with first-year students following the engineering curriculum.<ref name=McGillFifties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/fifties|title=The School with John Bland:1950s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=9 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133207/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/fifties|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> During the early 1950s, three new teachers were added to the faculty, including Hazen Sise and Guy Desbarats who later founded [[Arcop]] with Fred Lebensold, [[Ray Affleck]], and [[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]]&nbsp;\u2013 all former students or teachers of the School.<ref name=Arcop /> \n\n[[File:McConnell Engineering Building 2007.jpg|thumb|200px|upright|The [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#Buildings & Laboratories|McConnell Engineering Building]] in 2007, home to the School from 1959 until 1987.]]\nIn January 1958, the School was temporarily relocated to two townhouses on [[McTavish Street]] when the University Street building was demolished for the construction of the McConnell Building. On November 30, 1959, the new building was inaugurated and the School of Architecture moved to its north-eastern wing, where it remained for decades. Enrollment was steady during the 1950s due to the limitations of physical space, but after the McConnell Building underwent a four-story expansion in the 1960s enrollment grew again.<ref name=McGillFifties />\n\nIn 1961, McGill Professor Douglas Shadbolt left the School to found the first architecture program at the Nova Scotia Technical College (later known as [[Technical University of Nova Scotia|Technical University of Nova Scotia]] [TUNS]) in [[Halifax, Canada|Halifax]], and 8 years later founded the School of Architecture (later the Azrieli School of Architecture and Urbanism) at [[Carleton University]] in [[Ottawa, Ontario]].<ref name=Shadbolt>{{cite web|url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-shadbolt|title=Douglas Shadbolt|publisher=The Canadian Encyclopedia|author=Michael McMordie|date=16 December 2013|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327180624/https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/douglas-shadbolt|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In 1966, [[John C. Parkin]] and [[Harry Mayerovitch]] joined the faculty as visiting professors. In the following years, [[Ray Affleck]], Fred Lebensold, [[Eva Vecsei|Andre Vecsei]], [[Warren Chalk]] and [[Moshe Safdie]] also became visiting professors.<ref name=McGillSixties>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/sixties|title=The School with John Bland:1960s, History by Norbert Schoenauer|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=15 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200115133331/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school/history/sixties|archive-date=15 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn the late 1960s, the six-year architecture program became a four-year program with the introduction of [[CEGEP]]s in Quebec.<ref name=McGillSixties />\n\n===1970\u2013present===\nIn 1970, Spence-Sales retired from the faculty. Later that year, the graduate planning program was restructured by Professor David Farley, which resulted in the establishment of the independent School of Urban Planning. Over the next decade and a half, the School changed directorship three times, with Professor Norbert Schoenauer heading the School from 1972 until 1975, Professor Derek Drummond from 1975 until 1985 and Professor Bruce Anderson in 1985.<ref name=Highlights />\n\nIn 1987, the School moved from the Engineering building to the [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]].<ref name=Highlights /> Macdonald-Harrington was initially named the Macdonald Chemistry Building but was renamed after Bernard Harrington, the building's first chemistry professor. The building is one of the many donations made by [[William Christopher Macdonald|Sir William Macdonald]] and was designed by Sir Andrew Taylor for the Departments of Chemistry and Mining in 1896. The building was renovated for the architecture and urban planning departments by [[Arcop]] in 1987.<ref name=CAC />\n\nIn 1989, the School of Architecture's PhD program was introduced. In 1990, Derek Drummond returned for another six years as the School's director, replaced by Professor David Covo in 1996. In 1997, the PhD program was officially approved by the Minister of Education<ref name=Highlights /> as the first in Canada,<ref name=CanadianArchitect /> and the School had its first PhD graduate, Lily Chi. In 1999, the professional BArch degree was replaced by the new MArch&nbsp;I professional degree, leaving the BSc in architecture as the only undergraduate architecture degree. Two years later, the School graduated its first class in the MArch&nbsp;I program.<ref name=Highlights /> \n\nIn 2003, philanthropist [[David Azrieli]] endowed an annual lecture at the School, called the [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture Series|David J. Azrieli Lecture Series]].<ref name=Highlights /> In 2005, McGill Architecture graduate [[Gluskin Sheff|Gerald Sheff]] endowed the Gerald Sheff Visiting Professorship in Architecture faculty position, which enabled the recruitment of leading individuals in architecture to teach at the School. The first appointee in 2006 was [[Dan Hanganu]], and subsequent hires include John Shnier (the first Canadian to win the [[Prix de Rome (Canada)|Prix de Rome]] in Architecture), [[Steve Badanes]], [[Atelier TAG]], Matthew Lella (partner at [[Diamond Schmitt Architects]]), and [[Saucier + Perrotte|Gilles Saucier]].<ref name=Sheff>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/sheffprofessor|title=Gerald Sheff Visiting Professorship in Architecture|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=11 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nAfter an 11-year tenure as director, Covo stepped down and Professor [[Michael Jemtrud]] became director of the School in 2007. The next year, Jemtrud founded the [[McGill School of Architecture#FARMM|Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM)]] at the School of Architecture with more than $1&nbsp;million in funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://ca.linkedin.com/company/facility-for-architectural-research-in-media-and-mediation-farmm-|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM)|website=LinkedIn|accessdate=23 March 2020}}</ref> FARMM produced many award-winning projects and serves as the research hub for the School.<ref name=FARMM>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/farmm|title=Facility for Architectural Research in Media Mediation|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=23 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220643/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/farmm|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Professor [[Annmarie Adams]] became the first female director of the School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://reporter.mcgill.ca/with-annmarie-adams-director-of-the-school-of-architecture/|title=With Annmarie Adams, Director of McGill's School of Architecture|publisher=McGill Reporter|date=1 December 2011|author=Neale McDevitt|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> Since 2015, the director has been Professor Martin Bressani.<ref name=Highlights>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/school|title=Highlights of the School's History|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=30 December 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427200526/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/school|archive-date=27 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Directors===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! Director !! Tenure<ref name=Highlights />\n|-\n| [[Stewart Henbest Capper]] || 1896\u20131903 \n|-\n| [[Percy Nobbs]] || 1903\u20131913\n|-\n| [[Ramsay Traquair (architect)|Ramsay Traquair]] || 1913\u20131939\n|-\n| [[Philip J. Turner]] || 1939\u20131941\n|-\n| [[John Bland (architect)|John Bland]] || 1941\u20131972\n|-\n| Norbert Schoenauer || 1972\u20131975\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1975\u20131985\n|-\n| Bruce Anderson || 1985\u20131990\n|-\n| Derek Drummond || 1990\u20131996\n|-\n| David Covo || 1996\u20132007\n|-\n| [[Michael Jemtrud]] || 2007\u20132011\n|-\n| [[Annmarie Adams]] || 2011\u20132015\n|-\n|Martin Bressani\n|2015\u2013present\n|}\n\n==Buildings and resources==\n===Macdonald-Harrington Building===\n[[File:McGill University Building3.jpg|thumb|upright|The [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]], home to the McGill School of Architecture since 1987.]]\nThe [[Macdonald-Harrington Building]] is the home of the Peter Guo-hua School of Architecture, and also contains the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#School of Urban Planning|School of Urban Planning]] on the fourth level.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/facilities/buildings/macdonald-harrington|title=Macdonald-Harrington Building|publisher=McGill Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318044101/https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/facilities/buildings/macdonald-harrington|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=UrbanPlanning>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/urbanplanning/|title=School of Urban Planning|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323173314/https://www.mcgill.ca/urbanplanning/|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><!--A few instances on this page does it mention that the School of Urban Planning is located on the fourth floor (ex. bottom left of page)--> As architecture students progress through the years of the undergraduate program, they move through the design studios as well, with each year's respective studio located on a different level of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. The Master's studios are located on the top level,<ref name=CACB2 /> while the PhD studios are located on the same level as the first-year undergraduate studios and the School's administration.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/postprofstudio|title=Post-Professional Graduate Studio|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121115122442/http://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/postprofstudio|archive-date=15 November 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> The ground level, which can be accessed from the Frank Dawson Adams (FDA) building,<ref name=Map>{{cite web|url=https://maps.mcgill.ca/?lat=45.50559139299993&lng=-73.57612234168278&z=16.000000&id=MacdonaldHarr|title=McGill University Interactive Campus Map|publisher=McGill Campus Maps|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> contains the lecture hall known as \"G-10\", which hosts [[McGill School of Architecture#Lecture series|the School's lecture series]].<ref name=LectureSeries>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures|title=Lecture Series|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=16 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327182540/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The ground floor also contains the [[McGill School of Architecture#Architecture Students' Association (ASA)|Architecture Students' Association (ASA)]] Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits,<ref name=SupplyStore>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/asa.supplystore/|title=ASA Supply Store|publisher=Architecture Students' Association|website=Facebook|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> as well as the architecture student lounge, known as the \"Cellar\", which is accessible 24/7 to architecture students.<ref name=Cellar>{{cite web|url=https://eus.wiki/Departmental_Lounges|title=Departmental Lounges|website=EUS (Engineering Undergraduate Society) Wiki|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327183018/https://eus.wiki/Departmental_Lounges|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The first floor, above the ground level, contains the second-year undegraduate studio as well as three \"crit rooms\", where project critiques are given, and the largest among them the \"exhibition room\" due to its common hosting of exhibitions of students' and outside guests' work. The third-year undergraduate studios are located on the third floor of Macdonald-Harrington.<ref name=CACB2>{{cite web|url=https://cacb.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/2018-McGill_University-VTR.pdf|title=2018 Visiting Team Report - Master of Architecture Program - McGill University|publisher=The Canadian Architectural Certification Board|page=19|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Workshop====\nThe multi-level workshop is located in the basement and ground floor of the Macdonald-Harrington building, and provides students with all of their model-making needs. The workshop contains various equipment and power tools for working with wood, plaster, glass, acrylics and metal, and also contains other facilities, including a fumehood for sandblasting, spray painting, casting and mould-making. Workshop facilities include a Laser Cutting Room with three Universal Laser Cutter machines that students can use free-of-charge to cut and engrave acrylic, MDF, wood, styrene and other sheet materials. The workshop also includes 3D-printing machines, two of which are located inside the third-year studios on the third floor. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/workshop|title=Workshop facilities|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220553/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/workshop|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nMcGill University as a whole has a 3D-printing hub called \"the Cube\" which offers 3D-printing services to McGill students.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uprint3d.xyz/|title=The Cube, McGill University|accessdate=23 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229114137/http://uprint3d.xyz/|archive-date=29 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Media Centre====\nThe Media Centre is located in the Macdonald-Harrington building and is available exclusively to architecture students, faculty and staff at McGill.  \nThe Centre includes a traditional dark room for developing film photographs, a photography studio/light room for students to photograph their work as well as a printing room with multiple large format printers and scanners. The Media Centre also lends out digital cameras, lenses, tripods and light tents to students.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/media-centre|title=Media Centre|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220616/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/media-centre|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><!--cleaned up the copyright issues-->\n\n====FARMM====\nThe Facility for Architectural Research in Media and Mediation (FARMM) is the research hub of the McGill School of Architecture, located on the first floor of the Macdonald-Harrington Building. Founded in 2008 with funding from the [[Canada Foundation for Innovation]], FARMM connects students and researchers with colleagues internationally, and provides modern infrastructure for simulation, imaging, and fabrication.<ref name=FARMM />\n\n===Libraries and collections===\n====John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection====\n[[File:WCNA 2017 - Canadian Architecture Collection tour group in McLennan.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Tour of the CAC, 2017]]\nThe [[Canadian Architecture Collection]] (CAC) is one of the [[McGill University Library|McGill Libraries]]' Special Collections. It is located on the fourth floor of the [[Redpath Library]] building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/historicalcollections/library-archival/john-bland|title=John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection - Heritage|publisher=McGill University Historical Collections|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328192042/https://www.mcgill.ca/historicalcollections/library-archival/john-bland|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Students and professors at the Schools of Architecture and Urban Planning are required to document their work and entrust it with the Canadian Architecture Collection for safe-keeping, and several Canadian architects also bequeath their archives to the collection.\n\nAs of 2020, the Collection consisted of over 200,000 drawings, photographs, slides, models and maps as well as 400 metres of papers of nineteenth- and twentieth-century architects in Canada.<ref name=JBCAC>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/collection|title=John Bland Canadian Architecture Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220547/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/collection|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The largest fond of major Canadian architects is that of [[Moshe Safdie]], who donated his archives to the collection with an ongoing bequest since 1990.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cac.mcgill.ca/moshesafdie/history.html|title=The Moshe Safdie Archive|publisher=McGill Library|accessdate=13 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190821211053/http://cac.mcgill.ca/moshesafdie/history.html|archive-date=21 August 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The CAC also includes at least 770 papers from the course \"History of Architecture in Canada\".<ref name=JBCAC />\n\n====Architecture Slide Library====\nThe Architecture Slide Library contains more than 40,000 images, of which nineteenth- and twentieth-century images are the most heavily used. They are stored in Room 310 of the Macdonald-Harrington building, while slides from earlier periods are stored in the Media Centre.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/slides|title=Architecture Slide Library|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220517/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/slides|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection====\nThe Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection contains over two hundred scale  architectural models of structures from around the world. The models were created out of [[Plasticine|Roma Plastilina]] between 1940 and 1990 by Orson Wheeler,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/model|title=Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220546/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/model|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> a sculptor and former professor at McGill's School of Architecture.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/orson-wheeler|title=Orson Wheeler|publisher=National Gallery of Canada|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180117005641/https://www.gallery.ca/collection/artist/orson-wheeler|archive-date=17 January 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nA small collection of 40 works are on display in the front vestibule of the Macdonald-Harrington building.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/historicalcollections/departmental/orson-wheeler|title=Orson Wheeler Architectural Model Collection - Heritage|publisher=McGill University Historical Collections|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art====\nThe Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art is the University's parent library for the Schools of Architecture and Urban Planning, and is located on the upper floor of the Humanities and Social Sciences Library.\n\nThe library was established through a donation from the family of Gordon H. Blackader, one of the first students to study at the School of Architecture who died during World War&nbsp;I. The library was renamed the Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art during the 1940s after the family of sculptor [[Dinah Lauterman]] made a donation to the university in her memory.<ref name=Blackader>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/library|title=Blackader-Lauterman Library of Architecture and Art|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200112220520/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/resources/library|archive-date=12 January 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe library contains over 79,000 monographs and journal subscriptions, and has a substantial collection of over 3000 rare books from 1511 to 2009 housed in the [[Rare Books and Special Collections Library]] at McGill.<ref name=Blackader /> This includes a collection of original works by [[Vitruvius]], [[Palladio]], and [[G.&nbsp;B. Piranesi]], among others.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/historicalcollections/library-archival/blackader-lauterman|title=Blackader-Lauterman Collection - Heritage|publisher=McGill University Historical Collections|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190328191809/https://www.mcgill.ca/historicalcollections/library-archival/blackader-lauterman|archive-date=28 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Centre Canadien Architecture Montreal.JPG|thumb|220px|right|[[Canadian Centre for Architecture]], view of Shaughnessy House.]]\nOrs\n===Partnerships===\n====Canadian Centre for Architecture====\nThe School of Architecture maintains ties with the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] (CCA), which houses one of the largest architectural design collections in the world,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/news/2019/02/the-government-of-canada-supports-the-canadian-centre-for-architecture.html|title=The Government of Canada supports the Canadian Centre for Architecture|publisher=Government of Canada|date=11 February 2019|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323014750/https://www.canada.ca/en/canadian-heritage/news/2019/02/the-government-of-canada-supports-the-canadian-centre-for-architecture.html|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> a 20-minute walk away from the downtown campus. The CCA collaborates regularly with the School, and together organized the 2019 CCA Interuniversity [[Charrette]] which took place over a week in November and involved more than 10 universities in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cca.qc.ca/charrette/2019/en/index.html|title=About, CCA Interuniversity Charette|publisher=Canadian Centre for Architecture|accessdate=22 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323014339/https://www.cca.qc.ca/charrette/2019/en/index.html|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n===Student associations===\n====Architecture Students' Association (ASA)====\nThe Architecture Students' Association (ASA) is a society within the School of Architecture that is not-for-profit and student-run. The society represents all undergraduate students in the School of Architecture, organizes student activities and affairs and speaks for students regarding issues at McGill.<ref name=ASA>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/engineering/students/undergraduate/student-life/student-groups-associations|title=Student Groups & Associations, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=18 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190601201302/https://mcgill.ca/engineering/students/undergraduate/student-life/student-groups-associations|archive-date=1 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The ASA is chaired by the President and run by a council of six Vice-President portfolios: Academic, Internal, External, Administration, Finance and Student Life. A student representative from each undergraduate year is also elected to sit on the Council. \n\nPart of the ASA's mandate is to maintain the ASA Supply Store where students can purchase drafting kits as well as the architecture lounge, also known as the \"Cellar\".<ref name=Cellar /> Since 2011, the ASA has been part of the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering#Engineering Undergraduate Society (EUS)|Engineering Undergraduate Society (EUS)]] at McGill, and is also a member of the Canadian Architecture Students' Association (CASA).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.casa-acea.org/schools|title=Schools|publisher=Canadian Architecture Students' Association|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA)====\nThe McGill Graduate Architecture Students' Association (GASA) is a student-run society representing all graduate students at the School of Architecture. GASA is known to hold \"Late Night\" events on Thursdays, popular among students from all programs in the School.<ref name=GASA>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engage/overview/faculty-and-school-associations/graduate-faculty-and-school-associations|title=Graduate Faculty and School Associations, Engage McGill|accessdate=18 January 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190216044535/https://mcgill.ca/engage/overview/faculty-and-school-associations/graduate-faculty-and-school-associations|archive-date=16 February 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====American Institute of Architecture Students (AIAS)====\nAs of 2019, the School of Architecture has established a chapter of the [[American Institute of Architecture Students]], an international, non-profit, student-run organization dedicated to providing progressive programs, information and resources on critical issues to architecture students.<ref name=AIAS>{{cite web|url=http://www.aias.org/chapter/mcgill-university/|title=McGill University, Northeast Quad|publisher=American Institute of Architecture Students/accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Exchange and Study Abroad===\nThe Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture has close ties to several architecture schools across the world and has formal bilateral exchange agreements on a departmental level with seven schools in particular, including [[The Royal Danish Academy of Fine Arts]] in [[Copenhagen]], [[Politecnico di Milano]] in [[Milan]], [[Tongji University]] in [[Shanghai]], [[\u00c9cole Nationale Sup\u00e9rieure d'Architecture de Paris-Belleville]], [[:fr:\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble|\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'architecture de Grenoble]], [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]] in [[Brussels]] and [[TU Wien]] in [[Vienna]]. These bilateral agreements make it easy for undergraduate architecture students at McGill to go on exchange.<ref name =Exchange>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/files/architecture/bscarch_programadvisingandcourseregistration-fall_2018.pdf|title=B.Sc.(Arch.) program and Architecture Exchange Students (New and Returning Students) - STUDENT EXCHANGES|page=5|publisher=McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327190156/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/files/architecture/bscarch_programadvisingandcourseregistration-fall_2018.pdf|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\nStudents can also spend an exchange semester abroad at any of McGill University's 160+ partner institutions<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/mcgillabroad/mcgill-students-going-abroad/global-learning-opportunities|title=McGill students going abroad|publisher=McGill Abroad, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327184450/https://www.mcgill.ca/mcgillabroad/mcgill-students-going-abroad/global-learning-opportunities|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> as long as they offer architecture exchanges, however these are more difficult to coordinate due to the competitive nature of University-wide exchanges.<!--\"In addition to the seven schools with whom the School of Architecture has bilateral agreements, architecture students have spent exchange semesters at some of the top architecture schools in the world, including [[The Bartlett]] at [[University College London (UCL)]], [[National University of Singapore]], [[University of Leeds]], [[University of Liverpool]], [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Australian National University]].\" (Will include once I find a reliable source) -->\n\n==Organization and administration==\nThe School of Architecture reports to the Dean of the [[McGill University Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering at McGill]].<ref name=Highlights /> Due to its small size, the School is attached to the Faculty of Engineering for administrative purposes, but stands apart from the engineering departments and is headed by a director rather than a chairman.<ref name=McGillForties /> As of 2020, the School's faculty consists of 44 academic staff<ref name=Faculty /> and seven administrative and technical staff.<ref name=Staff /> The current director is Professor Martin Bressani.<ref name=Faculty /> As of 2018, student to faculty ratios fall between 12:1 and 15:1 for design studios, as established by the Canadian Architectural Certification Board (CACB). Students are often employed as part-time assistants to allow for greater access to facilities within the School.<ref name=CACB />\n\nThe School has been the recipient of several endowments, including over 50 scholarships and awards, over a dozen fellowships,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/scholarships|title=Scholarships, fellowships, prizes and fees|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|accessdate=12 April 2020}}</ref> several lecture series<ref name=LectureSeries /> and a [[Canadian dollar|C]]$1 million donation from [[Gluskin Sheff|Gluskin Sheff + Associates]] in 2005, subsequently matched by the School in 2008 to fund the annual Gerald Sheff Visiting Professorship in Architecture.<ref name=Sheff /> On September 26, 2017, the School was the recipient of a $12 million gift from Chinese architect and McGill graduate Peter Guo-hua Fu, which resulted in the renaming of the School.<ref name=Fu /> According to the CACB, approximately $500,000 of this donation is being employed annually outside of the School's base operating budget.<ref name=CACB /><!-- Created this section following the guidelines of the [[Wikipedia:College and university article guideline#Article structure|Organization and Administration section]] of an College/University article. -->\n\n==Academics==\nThe School of Architecture offers a professional program in Architecture comprising a Bachelor of Science in Architecture (BSc[Arch]) and professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree, as well as post-professional graduate programs leading to a Doctor of Philosophy (PhD) and post-professional Master of Architecture (MArch) degree. The School has a reputation for excellence in teaching, with all of its professors being either practicing architects or holding professional degrees and/or PhDs,<ref name=Faculty /> and architecture professors often being awarded teaching awards proportionately more often than other departments within the Faculty of Engineering relative to their respective sizes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/teaching-research-and-service-awards|title=Teaching, Research & Service Awards, Faculty of Engineering|accessdate=8 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200318044107/https://www.mcgill.ca/engineering/faculty-staff/teaching-research-and-service-awards|archive-date=18 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Professional programs===\n* '''BSc(Arch)''' \u2013 3 years, 100 credits\n* '''MArch (Professional)''':\n** Design Studio \u2013 1.5 years, 45 credits, or\n** Design Studio (Directed Research) \u2013 2 years, 60 credits\n\nIn Canada, the MArch (Professional) degree is accredited by the [[Professional requirements for architects#Canada|Canadian Architectural Certification Board]] (CACB), and is recognized in the United States by the [[National Council of Architectural Registration Boards]] (NCARB).<ref name=Accreditation />\n\n===Post-professional research programs===\n* '''MArch (Non-Thesis)''':\n** Architectural History and Theory \u2013 45 credits\n** Urban Design and Housing \u2013 45 credits\n* '''PhD'''\n<ref name=Programs />\n\n===Admissions===\nThe McGill School of Architecture has the smallest undergraduate entering class of any architecture school in Canada, as well as one of the smallest professional Master of Architecture programs.<ref name=Stats /> With a maximum capacity of 48 undergraduate students in the first year undergraduate studio (BSc[Arch]) and 35 students in both of the Master's (MArch&nbsp;1 and MArch&nbsp;II) studios,<ref name=CACB /> the School has one of the most selective and competitive sets of program offerings in the country with one of the lowest overall application-to-acceptance ratios.<ref name=Stats>{{cite web|url=https://www.acsa-arch.org/resources/data-resources/vital-statistics-on-canadian-schools-of-architecture/|title=Vital Statistics on Canadian Schools of Architecture|publisher=Association of Collegiate Schools of Architecture (ACSA)|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nGenerally, about 5\u201310 students from outside Quebec who plan to study architecture for their undergraduate degree will spend their first year at McGill in \"U0\", taking the necessary engineering prerequisites required for the 3-year BSc (Architecture) program at the School of Architecture. Students coming from Quebec [[CEGEP]]s enter directly into the BSc (Architecture) program, or first-year undergraduate (U1), but are required to have received a [[Diploma of college studies|DEC]] in either pure and applied science or health sciences, as these degrees fulfill the engineering prerequisites for the Architecture program.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/professional#application|title=Application procedures|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200323052948/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/programs/professional#application|archive-date=23 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=CACB />\n\nOffers of acceptance into the program are based on a unique review process including an evaluation of a portfolio of works and extracurricular involvement, in addition to grades. In the 2010\u20132011 academic year, there were 687 applications with portfolios to the undergraduate BSc Architecture program with only 51 spaces, giving an overall applications to enrolments ratio of 7.42%.<ref name=Admissions>{{cite web | url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf | title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.13 Section 2.0: Academic Programs, Teaching and Learning | year=2011 | accessdate=16 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701050716/https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf | archive-date=1 July 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> As of 2018, the number of spaces has been reduced to 48.<ref name=CACB>{{cite web|url=https://cacb.ca/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/2018-McGill_University-VTR.pdf|title=2018 Visiting Team Report - Master of Architecture Program - McGill University|publisher=The Canadian Architectural Certification Board|page=16|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref> With the exception of the new Bioengineering degree at McGill, for Quebec [[CEGEP]] students, admissions to the School of Architecture represent the highest average [[R score]] of students accepted into the Faculty of Engineering<ref>{{cite web | url=https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf | title=McGill School of Architecture: 2011 Cyclical Academic Unit Review, p.39 Section 2.7.1 Admissions | year=2011 | accessdate=16 January 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130701050716/https://info.publicintelligence.net/McGillSoA-AUR.pdf | archive-date=1 July 2013 | url-status=live }}</ref> however in contrast to the high average R score, the lowest score admitted can sometimes be closer to the engineering average due to the importance of the portfolio in the admissions process.\n\nEach year, the Master's program receives over 200 applicants, of which approximately 35 are admitted. Generally, about half of these students obtain their undergraduate degree from McGill, either from the BSc (Arch) program or another at the university.<ref name=CACB />\n\nThe School of Architecture has one of the highest percentages of female representation at McGill, with an overall ratio of female-to-male students of approximately 2:1. As of fall&nbsp;2019, there were 119 female and 44 male undergraduate students, and 54 female and 36 male graduate students enrolled at the School.<ref name=Enrollment />\n\n==Lecture series==\nEach year, the School of Architecture presents public lectures, exhibitions and symposia showcasing leading architects and important figures in the field. These lectures are organized by various individuals and organizations affiliated with the School. Lecture Series include lunchtime \"Brown Bag\" lectures organized by the McGill Architecture Students' Association, evening lectures sponsored by local Montreal firms such as Provencher Roy & [[NEUF Architect(e)s]],<ref name=LectureSeries /> and most notably, the annual [[David Azrieli|David J. Azrieli]] Lecture in Architecture which has brought in [[starchitect|starchitects]] from all over the world since 2003,<ref name=AzrieliLecture>{{cite web|url=https://mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures/azrieli|title=David J. Azrieli Lecture in Architecture|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture, McGill University|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200327182610/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/news-events/lectures/azrieli|archive-date=27 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> including seven [[Pritzker Prize]] laureates.{{NoteTag|Lecturers at McGill who have won the [[Pritzker Prize]] include [[Carme Pigem]], [[David Adjaye]], [[Thom Mayne]], [[Shigeru Ban]], [[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]], [[Glenn Murcutt]] and [[Jacques Herzog]].<ref name=Pritzker>{{cite web|url=https://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates|title=Laureates|publisher=The Hyatt Foundation|website=The Pritzker Architecture Prize|accessdate=27 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200405084430/https://www.pritzkerprize.com/laureates|archive-date=5 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>}}<ref name=Pritzker />\n\n===Notable lecturers===\n*[[Douglas Cardinal]] (2019\u20132020)<ref name=LectureSeries />\n*[[Carme Pigem]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Odile Decq]] (2018\u20132019)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Brigitte Shim|Brigitte Shim]] & [[Shim-Sutcliffe Architects|Howard Sutcliffe]] (2017\u20132018)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[David Adjaye]] (2016\u20132017)<ref name=AzrieliLecture /> \n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (2015\u20132016)<ref name=AzrieliLecture /><ref name=LectureSeries /> \n*[[Bruce Kuwabara]] (2014\u20132015)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Bjarke Ingels]] (2013\u20132014)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[J\u00fcrgen Mayer]] (2012\u20132013)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Thom Mayne]] (2011\u20132012)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Shigeru Ban]] (2010\u20132011)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Peter Eisenman]] (2009\u20132010)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Morphosis Architects|Michael Rotondi]] (2008\u20132009)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Moshe Safdie]] (2007\u20132008)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Reiser + Umemoto|Nanako Umemoto]] (2007\u20132008)<ref name=LectureSeries />\n*[[Paulo Mendes da Rocha]] (2006\u20132007)<ref name=AzrieliLecture /> \n*[[Glenn Murcutt]] (2005\u20132006)<ref name=AzrieliLecture /> \n*[[Daniel Libeskind]] (2004\u20132005)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Diamond Schmitt Architects|Jack Diamond]] (2004\u20132005)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Will Alsop]] (2002\u20132003, 2004\u20132005)<ref name=AzrieliLecture /> \n*[[Steven Holl]] (2003\u20132004)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n*[[Jacques Herzog]] (2002\u20132003)<ref name=AzrieliLecture />\n\n==Notable alumni and faculty==\n[[File:Raymond Moriyama.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Raymond Moriyama]], renowned architect of the [[Canadian War Museum]] and [[Scarborough Civic Centre]], graduated from McGill's MArch program in 1957.]]\n[[File:Arthur Erickson Portrait, 1984.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Erickson]], architect of the [[Museum of Glass]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]], received his BArch degree from McGill in 1950.]]\n[[File:Moshe Safdie.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Moshe Safdie]], architect of [[Marina Bay Sands]] and [[Habitat 67]], which was originally conceived in his Master's thesis at McGill in 1961.]]\n[[File:Arthur Lismer.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Arthur Lismer]], a member of the [[Group of Seven (artists)|Group of Seven]], taught History of Art and Theory of Design, Freehand Drawing and Sketching School at the School of Architecture.]]\n[[File:Ernest Cormier.jpg|thumb|190px|[[Ernest Cormier]], renowned Art Deco architect, taught from 1919 to 1920.]]\n===Alumni===\n*[[Caruso St John|Adam Caruso]] (BArch 1986) &ndash; co-founder of [[Caruso St John]], [[Stirling Prize]] winner<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/caruso|last=Caruso|first=Adam|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|date=June 1998|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200343/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/caruso|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Alina Payne]] (BArch 1977) &ndash; professor of History of Art and Architecture at [[Harvard University]]<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/payne|last=Payne|first=Alina|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|date=10 March 1998|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200316/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/payne|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Amale Andraos]] (BArch 1996) &ndash; founder of New York-based architecture firm WORKac<ref>{{cite web|url=https://issuu.com/gsapp_digitalpublishing/docs/bulletin_15-16/232|title=Bulletin 15\u201316 |publisher=Columbia University|date= 3 December 2015|accessdate=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n*Andre Vecsei (MArch 1973) &ndash; co-founder of Vecsei Architects with wife [[Eva Vecsei]]<ref name=AndreVecsei>{{cite web|url=https://bluebeard.micro.org/about-the-author/|title=A cultured man who cheated death in Hungary|author=Alan Hustak|publisher=Montreal Gazette|accessdate=11 March 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120528191401/http://bluebeard.micro.org/about-the-author/|archive-date=28 May 2012|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Anne Cormier (BArch 1982) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier Big City, 1998 [[Prix de Rome (Canada)|Prix de Rome]] winner<ref name=AtelierBigCity>{{cite web|url=https://www.atelierbigcity.com/team|title=Atelier Big City / Cormier, Cohen, Davies, architects|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*Annie Lebel (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; co-founder of Atelier In Situ, 2001 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2 />\n*[[Arthur Erickson]] (BArch 1950) &ndash; architect of [[Robson Square]], the [[Embassy of Canada in Washington, D.C.|Canadian Embassy]] and [[Roy Thompson Hall]]<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/erickson|last=Erickson|first=Arthur|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|title=Alumni Interviews|date=17 February 1998|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200404/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/erickson|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Blanche Lemco van Ginkel|Blanche van Ginkel]] (BArch 1945) &ndash; first woman to head a faculty of architecture in Canada and be awarded a fellowship by the [[Royal Architectural Institute of Canada|RAIC]]<ref>Annmarie Adams, (2015). [http://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/blanche-lemco-van-ginkel/ Article: Blanche Lemco van Ginkel] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190901163902/https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/blanche-lemco-van-ginkel |date=2019-09-01 }}, Canadian Encyclopedia. Accessed April 14, 2019.</ref>\n*[[Catherine Mary Wisnicki|Catherine Chard Wisnicki]] (B. Arch. 1943) &ndash; first female architecture graduate at McGill and one of the first female registered architects in Canada<ref name=Wisnicki />\n*[[Dimitri Dimakopoulos]] (BArch 1955) &ndash; of [[Affleck, Desbarats, Dimakopoulos, Lebensold, Sise]], designed [[Place Ville-Marie]]<ref name=\"Collectif2012\">{{cite book|last=Collectif|first=|title=Place Ville Marie: Montreal's Shining Landmark|date=21 September 2012|publisher=Qu\u00e9bec Amerique|language=English|isbn=9782764411728|page=207}}</ref> and [[1000 de La Gauchetiere]]\n*[[Dorice Constance Brown Walford|Dorice Walford]] (MArch 1958) &ndash; one of the first Canadian women in architecture to specialize in designing buildings for institutions<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/walford|last=Walford|first=Dorice|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|title=Alumni Interviews|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|date=July 1999|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200628/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/walford|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Eric Bunge (BSc[Arch] 1989, BArch 1991) &ndash; [[American Institute of Architects|FAIA]], co-founder of nARCHITECTS, 2005 Prix de Rome winner<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.arch.columbia.edu/faculty/169-eric-bunge|title=Eric Bunge|publisher=Columbia GSAPP|accessdate=11 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Frances Bronet]] (BSc[Arch] 1977, BArch 1978) &ndash; president of the [[Pratt Institute]] in [[Brooklyn]], [[New York (state)|New York]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pratt.edu/the-institute/administration-resources/office-of-the-president/about/|title=Pratt Institute {{!}} The Institute {{!}} Administration and Resources {{!}} Office of the President {{!}} About Frances Bronet|website=www.pratt.edu|access-date=2019-12-08}}</ref>\n*[[Gavin Affleck]] (BArch 1985) &ndash; architect and son of [[Raymond Affleck|Ray Affleck]]<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/affleck|last=Affleck|first=Gavin|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|title=Alumni Interviews|date=13 November 1998|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200141/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/affleck|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Gerald Sheff (BArch 1964) &ndash; founder of [[Gluskin Sheff + Associates Inc.]] and benefactor of the Gluskin Sheff Travel Scholarship at McGill<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/sheff|last=Sheff|first=Gerald|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|title=Alumni Interviews|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190324140550/https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/sheff|archive-date=24 March 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Gregory Henriquez]] (MArch 1988) &ndash; Vancouver-based architect<ref>{{cite web|url=https://henriquezpartners.com/teams/gregory-henriquez/|title=Gregory Henriquez|publisher=Henriquez Partners|accessdate=9 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Arcop|Guy Desbarats]] (BArch 1948) &ndash; co-founder of Montreal-based architectural firm [[Arcop]]<ref>{{Cite interview|url=https://www.mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/desbarats|last=Desbarats|first=Guy|interviewer=Jim Donaldson|publisher=Peter Guo-hua Fu School of Architecture|title=Alumni Interviews|date=11 November 1998|accessdate=10 April 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200206200536/https://mcgill.ca/architecture/people-0/aluminterviews/desbarats|archive-date=6 February 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*Hal Ingberg (BSc[Arch] 1983, BArch 1985) &ndash; architect of [[Palais des congr\u00e8s de Montr\u00e9al]], 1993 Prix de Rome winner<ref name=Alumni2>{{cite web|url=https://mcgillnews.mcgill.ca/s/1762/news/interior.aspx?sid=1762&gid=2&pgid=551|title=City builders, McGill Alumni|author=Daniel McCabe|publisher=McGill News Alumni Magazine|accessdate=11 March 2020|